\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Schematic contrast between correlation-based validity (left, five-step cycle) and the computational approach (right, five-step open chain). \emph  {Left}: The reasoning proceeds clockwise through steps 1--4 --- a general ability is assumed, used to predict task correlations, task correlations are observed, and those correlations are cited as evidence for indicator validity. The curved arrow from step 3 to step 5 marks the double-duty problem: the same correlational evidence simultaneously validates the indicators (step 4) and confirms the original ability assumption (step 5). The dashed arrow marks this closing link as the problematic step that makes the reasoning circular and non-falsifiable. \emph  {Right}: The computational approach shares the same five-step structure but does not close the loop. A formal theory is specified (1), cognitive processes are formalized as model parameters (2), data are generated from the model (3), and indicator validity is assessed via simulation (4). Step 5 --- cross-task correlations --- becomes an open empirical prediction rather than a definitional assumption, because the validity of each indicator has been established independently. The lightly shaded box (``Reproduce empirical effects'') represents an additional validation step in which simulated data from the model are checked against well-established qualitative patterns of empirical data; this model adequacy check constitutes a prerequisite before parameter-level validity can be meaningfully assessed.}}{11}{figure.caption.7}\protected@file@percent }
\providecommand*\caption@xref[2]{\@setref\relax\@undefined{#1}}
\newlabel{fig-circularity}{{1}{11}{Schematic contrast between correlation-based validity (left, five-step cycle) and the computational approach (right, five-step open chain). \emph {Left}: The reasoning proceeds clockwise through steps 1--4 --- a general ability is assumed, used to predict task correlations, task correlations are observed, and those correlations are cited as evidence for indicator validity. The curved arrow from step 3 to step 5 marks the double-duty problem: the same correlational evidence simultaneously validates the indicators (step 4) and confirms the original ability assumption (step 5). The dashed arrow marks this closing link as the problematic step that makes the reasoning circular and non-falsifiable. \emph {Right}: The computational approach shares the same five-step structure but does not close the loop. A formal theory is specified (1), cognitive processes are formalized as model parameters (2), data are generated from the model (3), and indicator validity is assessed via simulation (4). Step 5 --- cross-task correlations --- becomes an open empirical prediction rather than a definitional assumption, because the validity of each indicator has been established independently. The lightly shaded box (``Reproduce empirical effects'') represents an additional validation step in which simulated data from the model are checked against well-established qualitative patterns of empirical data; this model adequacy check constitutes a prerequisite before parameter-level validity can be meaningfully assessed}{figure.caption.7}{}}
