\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Conceptual illustration of the two generative models used in simulations. \textbf  {A (DMC, top left):} Mean evidence accumulation paths toward the correct response boundary (\emph  {a}) for congruent (blue solid) and incongruent (red dashed) conditions, starting at \emph  {z} = \emph  {a}/2. The dot-dashed line shows the pure controlled-drift asymptote \(\mu _c\). The horizontal bracket marks the RT difference score. \textbf  {A2 (DMC, bottom left):} Automatic activation component \(\mu _A\) characterised by the peak amplitude \(A\) and the time \(tau\) to reach this peak for both conditions (congruent: +, incongruent: −). \textbf  {B (SSP, right):} Attentional spotlight profiles (Gaussian weight over spatial position) at four successive time points. The solid vertical line marks the target; dashed lines mark flanker positions. The broad initial spread (sd\textsubscript  {0}, annotated in \emph  {t}\textsubscript  {1}) gives flankers substantial weight (``Flankers dominate''); The attentional weight for each stimulus in the spotlight modulates the perceptual evidence strength \(P\). As the spotlight narrows the target dominates, reversing the net drift direction.}}{17}{figure.caption.11}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig-model-architecture}{{2}{17}{Conceptual illustration of the two generative models used in simulations. \textbf {A (DMC, top left):} Mean evidence accumulation paths toward the correct response boundary (\emph {a}) for congruent (blue solid) and incongruent (red dashed) conditions, starting at \emph {z} = \emph {a}/2. The dot-dashed line shows the pure controlled-drift asymptote \(\mu _c\). The horizontal bracket marks the RT difference score. \textbf {A2 (DMC, bottom left):} Automatic activation component \(\mu _A\) characterised by the peak amplitude \(A\) and the time \(tau\) to reach this peak for both conditions (congruent: +, incongruent: −). \textbf {B (SSP, right):} Attentional spotlight profiles (Gaussian weight over spatial position) at four successive time points. The solid vertical line marks the target; dashed lines mark flanker positions. The broad initial spread (sd\textsubscript {0}, annotated in \emph {t}\textsubscript {1}) gives flankers substantial weight (``Flankers dominate''); The attentional weight for each stimulus in the spotlight modulates the perceptual evidence strength \(P\). As the spotlight narrows the target dominates, reversing the net drift direction}{figure.caption.11}{}}
